    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks, that helps a bit. but the socks thing feels like a metaphor. can you explain it more scientifically? like, why is it called \"spooky action at a distance\"? what's actually happening with the particles?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course! The term \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, who was puzzled by the idea of entanglement. In the quantum world, when two particles become entangled, their properties become linked in such a way that the state of one particle instantly influences the state of the other, no matter how far apart they are. This means that if you measure a property (like spin or polarization) of one entangled particle, you instantly know the property of the other particle, even if it's on the other side of the universe.\n\nThe \"spooky\" part comes from the fact that this connection seems to defy the classical idea that nothing can travel faster than the speed of light. In classical physics, information can't travel instantaneously, but in quantum entanglement, the results appear to be correlated instantly. This has led to many debates and discussions in the scientific community about the nature of reality and the limits of our understanding.\n\nIn essence, quantum entanglement challenges our classical notions of locality and causality, and it's one of the most fascinating and mysterious aspects of quantum mechanics. It's like having a pair of magical twin socks that can communicate instantly, no matter how far apart they are, defying the usual",
      "source": "target",
